{
  "doc_id": "9061",
  "text": "In the recent past, important advances have been made in algorithmic (automatic) phenotype analysis of somules; analogous methods do not yet exist for the adult stage of the parasite. In particular, methods have been developed for parasite segmentation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , parasite tracking from video recordings [CITATION_4] and quantitative identification of helminth phenotypes [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , including for hit detection in high-throughput screens [CITATION_7] and dose-response characterization [CITATION_8] . As yet, however, no automated method exists for identification of phenotypes and simultaneous determination/scoring of their severity. Therefore, we combined automated phenotypic analysis with manual phenotype assessment in an integrated analysis process and applied it to analyze the phenotypes arising from exposure of the parasites to the commercially available inhibitors and the PKIS 1 and 2 inhibitors.",
